<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-08-27T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-08-27T08:00:00-05:00" n="167" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 658.119/14</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_MIN1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Morris</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-08-27T14:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1917, 2 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 28, 12.40
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>682. On the 23d instant Swedish Minister for Foreign Affairs
                                delivered a public address in Stockholm in the course of which he
                                said that the Swedish Government would not sever commercial
                                relations with the Central powers as a condition to obtaining
                                foodstuffs from America. He stated that the population of Sweden
                                need not fear a famine during the coming year and that the
                                Government therefore will not be compelled to accept an agreement
                                which is unacceptable to the Swedish people. The Minister for
                                Foreign Affairs added, however, that the Government will endeavor to
                                come to an agreement with the United States. A copy of the address
                                is being forwarded to the Department by mail.<note n="1" xml:id="d167fn1">Not printed.</note>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1917Supp02v01#p_MIN1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>